				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Weapons<a name="7019"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">May 4 03 5:18 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>There are so many opinions on this, you have to go on a group by group basis.  
<br />

<br />
If I'm lucky enough that there's another bard in the group, I'll give 'em the melee package job and drop back and DoT.  Granted I'm 65, full song book, IM3, good drum.  At this level I don't think I've ever had an agro problem despite the fact that I'm outdamaging the MT, mainly because the MT has the gear and know-how to hold the agro.
<br />

<br />
If there's a chanter in the group that can supply the primary haste, you can just worry about the over haste.  Might as well, no matter how much haste you're throwing the tanks are still going to ask for chanter/shammy haste because they feel naked without the buff icon.
<br />

<br />
If you are the only haster in the group, then go full melee twist.  Haste/over haste/mana song/whatever else you like in the 4th spot.
<br />

<br />
I always have Manasong in the twist except when I'm solo kiting.
<br />

<br />
If you're lucky enough to have a haste proccing weapon (epic/Siren's Song Dagger of the Seas/Nature's Harmony) then you can let that look after the main haste and just over haste.  That is until you get to Warsong of Zek.  The other stuff that comes along with WoZ - str/attack buffs + Damage shield - are simply too nice to be without.
<br />

<br />
Overall, I've always meleed in groups except when popping the instruments up was crucial ... ie ... mezzing at earlier levels, or if the healing was a little light, then lute to help that out.
<br />

<br />
At higher levels with decent weapons and some AA investment a bard can do respectable melee damage.  I can now easily tank out the Kromriff Recruiter in Kael.  For those of you who haven't tried this, it's a test of DPS not damage absorption.  The riff Recruiter hits like a baby and is perma rooted, but he's 100 percent MR and as near as I can tell, regen's 20 percent of his HP every few ticks, so killing him solo is a great indicator of the damage you're putting out.
<br />

<br />
The best advice I can give you is get one-handed instruments as soon as you're able.  Lute of the Howler is the first one-handed instrument most people will have, not including the primary/secondary brass instrument that drops from greenies in Shadeweaver's Thicket (Flawless Ivory Horn).  Drum of the Beast (or better) is a must-have for any bard, although it's both rare and expensive.  One handed flute is nice for the earlier mezzes, but in all likelihood by the time you've done PoA enough times to get this item, you're well past the level where your mezzes are wind songs.  One-handed horns (apart from the Shadeweaver's Thicket one) are also high-lvl and rare.  One's from a PoA quest (worse then the flute quest) one's from NToV, and the best of the bunch pre-Elemental Planes drops rarely from a named Skelly in PoV.  Very nice horn, btw ... 2.8 mod on it, good stats.
<br />

<br />
One final note:  I've seen a few times bards swinging troub mace in main hand when they've got epic in off.  If you've got epic, toss away the troub mace.  The mod on it is only 1.3.
<br />

